{
  "text": "Orthoretroviral Gag proteins mediate the interaction with nucleic acids largely but not entirely by the Cterminal nucleocapsid (NC) domain (reviewed in [CITATION_1] ). They contain conserved motifs of regularly spaced cysteine and histidine residues (Cis-His), which are important for recognition of the complex structured packaging signal (called Psi) in the vgRNA [CITATION_2] . This specific mechanism allows selective vgRNA encapsidation in orthoretroviral particles (reviewed in [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ). However, orthoretroviral Gag proteins also possess additional non-specific RNA binding features and several types of retroviruses were found to encapsidate cellular RNAs constituting up to 50% of the particle-associated nucleic acid content [CITATION_5] . Most non-viral RNAs are packaged in a non-selective fashion, although in some cases a selective encapsidation is observed leading to their enrichment similar to vgRNA. The potential biological role of encapsidated host-cell RNAs for viral replication is largely unknown. Besides its participation in recognition and encapsidation of vgRNA the orthoretroviral NC domain has nucleic acid chaperone activities as well as additional functions in particle assembly and release, and timing of reverse transcription (RTr) (reviewed in [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] ).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "3452654",
    "[CITATION_2]": "29450376",
